  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_504623540" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/504623540" />
    <a title="Ted" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7213075-ted"><img alt="Ted" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1553101210p2/7213075.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/504623540?book_show_action=true">Jan 12, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ted" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ted" href="/user/show/7213075-ted">Ted</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7213075-ted?shelf=have">have</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7213075-ted?shelf=reviews-compartmented">reviews-compartmented</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7213075-ted?shelf=lit-irish">lit-irish</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7213075-ted?shelf=crime-fiction">crime-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7213075-ted?shelf=history">history</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7213075-ted?shelf=beach-fun-fiction">beach-fun-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7213075-ted?shelf=reviews-overflowed">reviews-overflowed</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer504623540" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1988811102130652962"><b>4 1/2</b><br/><br/><b>This is the longest review I&apos;ve ever written, and most isn&apos;t about the book itself.</b><br/><br/><b>The Ghosts of Belfast review, Part I<br/>Part II <a target='_blank' rel='noopener nofollow' href='https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/466705899'>http://www.goodreads.com/review/show/...</a><br/>Part III <a target='_blank' rel='noopener nofollow' href='https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/413328951'>http://www.goodreads.com/review/show/...</a> <br/>Part IV <a target='_blank' rel='noopener nofollow' href='https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/308745607'>http://www.goodreads.com/review/show/...</a> </b><br/><br/>First-novel thriller by Stuart Neville, won many awards and plaudits. Would have finished it in two days, but late the second night, maybe 40 pages to go, just wasn’t able to handle those pages, couldn’t bear to continue reading </span>
  <span id="freeText1988811102130652962" style="display:none"><b>4 1/2</b><br /><br /><b>This is the longest review I've ever written, and most isn't about the book itself.</b><br /><br /><b>The Ghosts of Belfast review, Part I<br />Part II <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/466705899">http://www.goodreads.com/review/show/...</a><br />Part III <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/413328951">http://www.goodreads.com/review/show/...</a> <br />Part IV <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/308745607">http://www.goodreads.com/review/show/...</a> </b><br /><br />First-novel thriller by Stuart Neville, won many awards and plaudits. Would have finished it in two days, but late the second night, maybe 40 pages to go, just wasn’t able to handle those pages, couldn’t bear to continue reading at that hour, mostly because of the presentiment of a horribly brutal conclusion. After sleeping on it, and in the (appropriately) gloomy light of day I was able to finish.<br /><br />Not really an “historical novel” in the sense that books like <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/6101138.Wolf_Hall__Thomas_Cromwell___1_" title="Wolf Hall (Thomas Cromwell, #1) by Hilary Mantel" rel="nofollow noopener">Wolf Hall</a> are, wherein <i>actual historic people</i> play minor or even major roles, and <i>real, specific historic events</i> are part of the story line. It is possible that one or two characters (unbeknownst to me) are patterned after actual people, and there is one key event in the book which is <i>similar</i> to an actual occurrence. (See 2nd spoiler section.) <br /><br />The story itself is a fast-paced page-turner, and has several unexpected plot-twists - but the high rating I’ve given the novel is for the way it caused me to delve into its backstory, the time of “The Troubles” in Northern Ireland. For that, see the spoiler section so-named.<br /><br />The following spoiler section of the review deals with the overall plot of the novel, discusses the main character, and makes some claims about other characters; without really going into many details, and without telling anything of the story’s resolution. <br /><br />However, before entering spoiler land, just a couple comments that may be of interest. First, the novel’s U.K./Ireland name is <i>The Twelve</i>. Second, this novel is now billed as “Jack Lennon Investigations #1”, with two more in the series already published. I’d be interested to know if this first novel had this billing when it was originally published, or whether it acquired it as a result of its popularity and acclaim by various critics. In other words, did Neville and his publisher decide that hey, we’d better get going on a series here … what can we call it? I make this comment because, as anyone knows who has read Twelve/Ghosts, at the end of the book, one might well say “Who the heck was Jack Lennon? Was there a character of that name?” Yes, he is in the book; he’s part of the <i>deep</i> backstory for one of the main characters, and plays no other part whatsoever in the plot; nor is he an “investigator” of anything, although he is a cop.<br /><br />Okay, on to the spoilers.<br /><br /><b>Neville’s characters</b><br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[<br />The story’s main character, and anti-hero, is Gerry Fegan, a former killer for the Provisional IRA. Fegan’s timeline, which is related in flashbacks, many in the form of his own ruminations, runs like this: he’s born sometime in the early ‘60s; when he’s nine his dad dies, right around the start of The Troubles; at the age of twenty (early ’80s) he does his first killing; then in 1988 he’s arrested for bombing a butcher shop on Shankill Road. The bomb, instead of killing Loyalists who were supposed to be meeting upstairs, kills the butcher, a woman customer, and her baby. (This bombing appears to be a fictional version of the famous Shankill Road bombing of 1993, which occurred in a <i>fish</i> shop under circumstances quite similar to those described in the story. (See <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shankill_Road_bombing">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shankill...</a>.) Gerry winds up in Maze Prison, with other paramilitary prisoners of all stripes (but mostly Catholics). At the age of 38, after 12 years behind bars, he’s released as the prison is being closed down. He spends the next seven years drifting and drinking, until the novel’s “present” arrives. The year is maybe 2007, Gerry is 45 years old.<br /><br />And Gerry is haunted - by the ghosts of the twelve people whose lives he took those many years ago. They scream, the wee one wails, he can’t sleep unless he’s drunk, and eventually comes to understand what they want of him – vengeance, not only on Gerry (by making his life unbearable) but on the superiors who gave the orders resulting in their deaths.<br /><br />To me, this is a pretty noir-ish novel. (Not meant as a criticism!) There aren’t any saints in it, no characters that are extremely likeable. I suppose Marie’s little girl is likeable, and Marie herself comes <i>close</i> to being likeable; you definitely feel that she’s been wronged, and you root for her. But I also rooted for Gerry, despite the fact that he’s certainly not portrayed as a very admirable fellow. Yes, he feels guilty about the lives he’s taken. At least that’s how the prison psychiatrist interprets his ghosts. But you know, a really “good” fellow would have some sort of change of heart. Gerry realizes that he’s been a blood-thirsty son of a bitch and that he’s paying the price for it, but rather than change his life he “expiates” his sins by doing what he does best – killing some more. Yet despite this, Neville succeeded in getting me at any rate to hope that Gerry made it through alive and vanquished his ghosts.<br /> <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />. . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .<br /><b>Previous review:</b> <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/684555021" rel="nofollow noopener">Riders of the Purple Sage</a> <i>Zane Grey</i><br /><b>Random review:</b> <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1739202155" rel="nofollow noopener">The Military Philosophers</a> <i>Powell's Dance</i><br /><b>Next review:</b> <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/711121209" rel="nofollow noopener">MaddAddam</a> <i>Atwood</i><br /><br /><b>Previous library review:</b> <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/256147336" rel="nofollow noopener">Brick Lane</a> <i>Monica Ali</i><br /><b>Next library review:</b> <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1673587546" rel="nofollow noopener">The House of Writers</a> <i>M.J. Nichols</i><br />. . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .<br /><br />Next spoiler represents why I gave the novel the high rating. It’s likely more than anyone will care to know about the background to this story, and will no doubt be quite unnecessary for readers in the U.K. and Ireland.<br /><br /><b>Backstory - The Troubles</b><br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[ (or, The Troubles: <u>A Very <i>Very <b>Very</b></i> Short Introduction.</u>)<br />This spoiler is organized into several topics, each hidden in its own spoiler section. Some topics have further organization.<br /><br />The backstory to the novel is the era of “The Troubles”. This is the phrase used to refer to the period 1969-2001 in which over 3500 people, almost all in Northern Ireland, lost their lives to violence perpetrated with the object of either forcing or preventing the unification of Northern Ireland with the Republic of Ireland. The beginning of this period is viewed by some to coincide with a series of civil rights marches staged mostly by members of the Catholic community, protesting various long-felt grievances. These took place in the months June – October of 1968 at various places in Northern Ireland. Many of the marches were disrupted by attackers, with marchers being beaten, etc. In August of the next year disorder culminated in the so-called Battle of the Bogside, three days of rioting in Derry. During this the first fatality of The Troubles occurred. Things went downhill from there.<br /><br />The novel really got me to thinking about The Troubles. Amazingly, or at least I’m sure it would be amazing to any reader from the British Isles or even Europe who glances at this review, I found I knew very little about The Troubles – other than a vague idea of when this era was, and some idea of the sectarian/religious nature of the conflict.<br /><br />The novel doesn’t give a reader like me much help in this area, though I don’t fault Neville for that. After all, he’s writing a novel, not a history book, and his Irish and U.K. audience knows this backstory a lot better than I do. <br /><br /><b><i>The Basics</i></b><br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[<br />“You’re a Republican hero.”<br /><br />The Wiki article on The Troubles, from which I got much of this information, states that <blockquote>The key issues at stake in the Troubles were the constitutional status of Northern Ireland and the relationship between its mainly Protestant unionist community and its mainly Catholic nationalist community. <b>Unionists and loyalists</b> generally want Northern Ireland to remain within the United Kingdom while Irish <b>nationalists and republicans</b> generally want it to leave the United Kingdom and join a united Ireland.</blockquote>(My emphasis. See <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Troubles">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Trou...</a>. ) Another site that has very organized information about the Troubles is <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/index.html">http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/index.html</a> <br /> <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br /><b><i>Main Players</i></b><br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[<br />Information in this section is from<br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Directory_of_the_Northern_Ireland_Troubles">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Director...</a> . This article is a comprehensive directory to a large number of the Wikipedia articles related to The Troubles. In listing these “Main Players” I have left out organizations that seem to be “minor” main players, usually because I had never heard of them <b>and</b> I don’t recall them being mentioned in the novel.<br /><br /><b><i>Republican Paramilitaries </i></b><br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[<br /><b>Provisional Irish Republican Army (PIRA).</b> The PIRA came into being in 1969 when the older IRA (in existence since the Irish War of Independence in 1919-1921) split “over differences of ideology and how to respond to violence against the nationalist community.” Throughout the 1960s the IRA had become increasingly influenced by left-wing thinkers (Marxists). By 1969 they had moved to a “class-based political outlook and the consequent rejection of any stance that could be seen as sectarian – including the use of IRA arms to defend one side, the beleaguered Catholic communities of Belfast”. As time passed, the “IRA” became more and more associated in many people’s minds (particularly those outside Northern Ireland) with the PIRA, since the PIRA was the group advocating and engaging in force to promote their goals. Thus, any time after the mid-1970s, if you see reference to an “IRA” action in the Troubles, it is likely the PIRA which is being referred to. The PIRA was responsible for more deaths during the Troubles than any other group, roughly 1800 or about half the total. About 1100 of these were security forces, with 600-650 of the remainder being civilians. (See <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Provisional_Irish_Republican_Army">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Provisio...</a> and <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irish_Republican_Army_%281922%E2%80%931969%29">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irish_Re...</a> ) <br /><br />There were, over the years of The Troubles, many paramilitary factions splitting off from both the PIRA and the Official IRA. Of these, the longest lived one was the <b>Irish National Liberation Army</b>. The INLA was formed in late 1974, and although it declared a ceasefire in 1998, it was not until 2009 that it “formally vowed to pursue its aims through peaceful political means.” From the beginning, its aims included not only removing Northern Ireland from the U.K., but also of creating a specifically socialist united Ireland. (See <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irish_National_Liberation_Army">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irish_Na...</a> ).<br /><br />“One insane act … had almost wiped the dissidents out. The disastrous bombing of Omagh …” (see <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Omagh_bombing">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Omagh_bo...</a> )<br /><br />Another PIRA splinter group is the <b>Real IRA (RIRA)</b>. This paramilitary was organized in 1997, refused to endorse the Belfast Agreement (see below), and was responsible for the Omagh bombing in 1998. Based on the quote from the novel given above, it is apparently the RIRA that Davy Campbell has become associated with in chapter 3. ( see <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_Irish_Republican_Army">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_Iri...</a> )<br /> <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br /><b><i>Loyalist Paramilitaries </i></b><br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[<br /> “two more were Loyalists, both Ulster Freedom Fighters”<br /><br />The longest lived and most important of these groups (there were many others) were the <b>Ulster Volunteer Force (UVF</b>, 1966-2007), and the <b>Ulster Defense Association (UDA)/Ulster Freedom Fighters (UFF)</b>, 1971-2007. The second two were in fact two faces of the same overall organization. The UFF was the name used by the UDA when they claimed responsibility for attacks; publicly it was claimed that they were two separate organizations. This tactic allowed the UDA to remain legal for over twenty years, until 1992, when the U.K. classified the UDA as a terrorist group. The UFF had been outlawed in 1973.<br /><br />The UDA, responsible for 260 killings during the Troubles, was the <i>largest</i> loyalist paramilitary group in Northern Ireland. Their older rival, the UVF, was the <i>deadliest</i> such group. According to one data base, the UVF and a closely linked group, the <b>Red Hand Commando (RHC)</b>, were responsible for 481 deaths over the years. 85% of these were civilians, almost all of those Catholics. Some of the UVF’s attacks were carried out in the Republic of Ireland.<br /><br />(See <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ulster_Volunteer_Force">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ulster_V...</a> and <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ulster_Defence_Association">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ulster_D...</a> )<br /> <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br /><b><i>Security Forces (U.K.)</i></b><br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[<br />“two (soldiers) were Ulster Defense Regiment”<br /><br />The British Army’s <b>Ulster Defense Regiment (UDR)</b>, the largest infantry regiment in the Army, became operational in 1970. It was initially formed with seven battalions, but four more were added within two years. The UDR’s mission was the “defense of life or property in Northern Ireland against armed attack or sabotage.” Of the UDR, Wikipedia states <blockquote> Recruiting from the local community at a time of intercommunal strife, it was accused of sectarian attitudes and collusion with loyalist paramilitary organizations through most of its term. The regiment was intended to be nonpartisan, and it began with Catholic recruits accounting for 18% of membership, however due to various circumstances by the end of 1972 the Catholic membership made up around 3% of the regiment's soldiers.</blockquote>The UDR was merged out of existence in 1992 when it was combined with the Royal Irish Rangers to form the <b>Royal Irish Regiment (RIR)</b>. This unit (or probably certain battalions of the combined unit – I can’t tell, honestly) took over the former duties of the UDR until the summer of 2006, when the part stationed in Northern Ireland was disbanded. <br />(See <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ulster_Defence_Regiment">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ulster_D...</a> &amp; <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Royal_Irish_Regiment_(1992)">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Royal_Ir...</a> )<br /><br />The participation of the Security Service (<b>Military Intelligence Section 5 - MI5</b>) was no doubt of particular importance during the Troubles. MI5 is the U.K.’s intelligence branch responsible for <i>internal</i> counter-intelligence and security. While MI5 and other intelligence forces have provided support “in the countering of both republican and loyalist paramilitary groups since the early 1970s, republican sources have often accused these forces of collusion with loyalists. In 2006, an Irish government committee inquiry found that there was widespread collusion between British security forces and loyalist terrorists in the 1970s, which resulted in eighteen deaths.” A full accounting of the roll which MI5 played in Northern Ireland during the Troubles has apparently yet to be written, presumably because much of this information is still classified. (See <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MI5">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MI5</a> )<br /><br />Many other segments of the U.K. Defense establishment were involved in Northern Ireland security over the years, including the Territorial Army, the Royal Air Force, the Royal Navy, and the Metropolitan Police.<br /> <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br /><b><i>Security Forces (Northern Ireland)</i></b><br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[<br />“Another … was a cop, his Royal Ulster Constabulary uniform neat and stiff”<br /><br />“Marie McKenna had scandalized her family by taking up with an officer of the hated Royal Ulster Constabulary” (the pretty minor character Jack Lennon!)<br /><br />The <b>Royal Ulster Constabulary (RUC)</b> was the name of Northern Ireland’s police force from 1922 to 2000. As The Troubles were beginning in the late ‘60s, an “exhaustive inquiry” into the disturbances and the policing situation was carried out by several high ranking members of the U.K. establishment, including James Callahan, the Home Secretary. A report was published in October 1969. As a result, a complete reorganization of the RUC was implemented, with the aim of “modernizing the force and bringing it into line with the other police forces in the UK”. <br /><br />The revamped RUC, particularly its Special Patrol Group (SPG - an anti-terrorist unit which operated from the early ‘70s to 1980), “are alleged to have colluded extensively with loyalist paramilitaries throughout the 30-year conflict in Northern Ireland.” Several reports and inquiries over the years established that at least some of these allegations had a factual basis, and two members of the SPG were actually convicted of terrorist activities. Because of this collusionist reputation, the RUC was a frequent target of Republican paramilitaries during The Troubles. Upwards of 300 RUC officers were killed in the years 1969 to 1998, with 277 of these killings attributed to Republican groups.<br />(See <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Royal_Ulster_Constabulary">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Royal_Ul...</a> )<br /><br />The <b>Ulster Special Constabulary (USC)</b> (commonly called the “B-Specials” or “B Men”) dated from 1920, and was still active in the very early years on the Troubles. However, it was disbanded in May 1970 as a result of the Hunt report. Wikipedia notes that “The force was almost exclusively Protestant and Unionist and as a result was viewed with great mistrust by Catholics and nationalists. During the 1920s, it carried out revenge killings and reprisals against Catholic civilians in the 1920–22 conflict.”<br />(See <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ulster_Special_Constabulary">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ulster_S...</a> )<br /> <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br /><b><i>Political Parties </i></b><br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[<br />This section is mainly a copy of <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Directory_of_the_Northern_Ireland_Troubles#Political_parties">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Director...</a> . None of these parties are mentioned in the novel by name. I assume that the political characters Michael McKenna and McGinty are members of Sinn Fein, as well as having been at one time members of the PIRA; though the Republican Sinn Fein is also a possibility. Each party’s stand on the Belfast Agreement is indicated.<br /><br /><b>Nationalist/Republican</b><br /><br />Sinn Féin (SF). Militant nationalist. Often associated with the Provisional IRA. Pro-Agreement.<br /><br />The Social Democratic and Labour Party (SDLP). Moderate centre-left nationalist. Pro-Agreement.<br /><br />The Irish Republican Socialist Party (IRSP). Militant nationalist. Political wing of INLA. Anti-Agreement.<br /><br />Republican Sinn Féin (RSF). Militant nationalist. Often associated with the Continuity IRA. Anti-Agreement.<br /><br />The 32 County Sovereignty Movement (32CSM). Militant Nationalist. Often associated with the Real IRA. Anti-Agreement.<br /><br />The Workers' Party (WP). Marxist nationalist. Formerly Official Sinn Féin. Pro-Agreement.<br /><br /><b>Unionist/Loyalist</b><br /><br />The Democratic Unionist Party (DUP). Radical populist unionist. Originally anti-Agreement; later pro-Agreement.<br /><br />The Ulster Unionist Party (UUP). Moderate conservative unionist. Pro-Agreement.<br /><br />The Progressive Unionist Party (PUP). Moderate centre-left unionist. Political wing of Ulster Volunteer Force. Pro-Agreement.<br /><br />The Conservative Party also organises and contests elections in Northern Ireland. Moderate unionist. Pro-Agreement.<br /><br /><b>Other</b><br /><br />The Alliance Party of Northern Ireland. Liberal cross-community. Pro-Agreement<br /><br />The Green Party. Environmentalist. Pro-Agreement.<br /><br />Ulster Third Way. Supports Northern Ireland independence.<br /> <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /> <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /> <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span></span>
  <a data-text-id="1988811102130652962" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
