<div id="review_557350719" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/557350719" />
    <a title="Laurel" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/15977158-laurel"><img alt="Laurel" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1357070199p2/15977158.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/557350719?book_show_action=true">Mar 10, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Laurel" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Laurel" href="/user/show/15977158-laurel">Laurel</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/11997408-the-ghosts-of-belfast">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/15977158-laurel?shelf=thriller">thriller</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/15977158-laurel?shelf=around-the-world">around-the-world</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/15977158-laurel?shelf=ebooks">ebooks</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/15977158-laurel?shelf=series">series</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/15977158-laurel?shelf=big-challenge">big-challenge</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer557350719" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5380882862123429213">One of the many benefits of Goodreads membership is that you are free to discover authors and books that take you outside of your comfort zone, if you so choose. Reading Stuart Neville&apos;s first thriller/crime novel certainly does that in spades! I chose this book for a variety of reasons. It has multiple award nominations for a first novel, glowing reviews from authors I admire and Goodread friends whose opinions I respect. Plus, I needed a book set in Ireland for a challenge. This is set in post</span>
  <span id="freeText5380882862123429213" style="display:none">One of the many benefits of Goodreads membership is that you are free to discover authors and books that take you outside of your comfort zone, if you so choose. Reading Stuart Neville's first thriller/crime novel certainly does that in spades! I chose this book for a variety of reasons. It has multiple award nominations for a first novel, glowing reviews from authors I admire and Goodread friends whose opinions I respect. Plus, I needed a book set in Ireland for a challenge. This is set in post 9-11 Belfast, and the old style of gasoline bombs in the streets and tit-for-tat assassinations are slowly and begrudgingly giving way to politicians and behind the scenes government manipulation. This is a brilliantly written, haunt your thoughts kind of story, but I did not enjoy it, nor can I say that I will try the next in the series, anytime soon, despite all the accolades it has garnered. Here's why. Although I felt great sympathy for Gerry Fegan the main character, when I reached the end, I did not like him. I understand why he did the things so blatantly described on these pages, but I felt little inclination to cheer him on. Redemption, although a noble objective, cannot be achieved through more bloodshed, to wipe away years of accumulated guilt. Neville's prose is incredibly descriptive, graphic and violent, as befits the environment of Fegan's Belfast, and during specific events in the bloody eighties and nineties. Fegan has been involved with the troubles his whole life, and took his first life at the tender age of eighteen. This book left me feeling sad, more than a little angry at the horrific waste of life, and quite grimy. If that was Neville's goal, he has accomplished it! I also realized that I know very little about this bloody time in Irish politics and social history- perhaps another goal achieved by the author, except that I am not ready to immediately begin the next book. As it turns out, I agree that Neville deserves the kudos he has received, but remain undecided if he can count me among his dedicated readers. </span>
  <a data-text-id="5380882862123429213" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


